WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.882 --> 00:00:04.299
(soft music)

00:00:36.164 --> 00:00:38.331
- I don't know how many
other Jefferson lecturers

00:00:38.331 --> 00:00:39.164
(audience laughs)

00:00:39.164 --> 00:00:41.330
put on their Revolutionary War hat,

00:00:41.330 --> 00:00:46.330
but I will deliver part of
the lecture with my hat on.

00:00:49.010 --> 00:00:52.273
So I'm gonna talk about three things,

00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:57.180
and they will get increasingly speculative

00:00:57.180 --> 00:01:00.590
as we move along, so
I'll give you some facts

00:01:01.550 --> 00:01:02.770
about the inequality and globalization

00:01:02.770 --> 00:01:05.520
and the ways that I think
they challenge our democracy,

00:01:06.605 --> 00:01:08.640
and then, the most speculative part

00:01:08.640 --> 00:01:10.430
will be how we're gonna
meet these challenges,

00:01:10.430 --> 00:01:12.370
or how we can meet them.

00:01:12.370 --> 00:01:14.080
And there is Hamilton, actually,

00:01:14.080 --> 00:01:17.640
on the $10 bill, and I
thought about putting

00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:22.010
Jefferson, he's on the two dollar bill,

00:01:22.010 --> 00:01:23.563
and he's also on the nickel.

00:01:27.784 --> 00:01:31.160
This is basically the
theme I wanna go through.

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:36.160
The threat we see from
inequality is that wealthy people

00:01:37.070 --> 00:01:40.320
can use money to protect their money,

00:01:40.320 --> 00:01:44.650
and that was a deep concern
of Mr. Jefferson, indeed,

00:01:44.650 --> 00:01:48.990
and then, globalization, the concern is,

00:01:48.990 --> 00:01:51.550
it doesn't matter what the state does,

00:01:51.550 --> 00:01:55.490
the state can't tax as much,
'cause capital is very mobile,

00:01:55.490 --> 00:01:57.260
so it can't redistribute income

00:01:57.260 --> 00:02:02.260
from the upper income groups
to the lower income groups,

00:02:02.460 --> 00:02:04.610
and those are the two principle specters,

00:02:04.610 --> 00:02:07.950
that inequality weakens the democracy,

00:02:07.950 --> 00:02:12.065
and then even when the government
might wanna do something,

00:02:12.065 --> 00:02:15.462
the globalization says, No, you can't.

00:02:15.462 --> 00:02:19.713
And then, the word feudalistic is more

00:02:19.713 --> 00:02:23.703
of a word used in Jefferson's time,

00:02:25.416 --> 00:02:27.160
when we think about multi-nationals

00:02:28.423 --> 00:02:29.950
and super wealthy folks making decisions,

00:02:29.950 --> 00:02:32.760
and then I had to add in to this quote,

00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:34.920
the potential villains in this piece

00:02:34.920 --> 00:02:37.950
are people like many of the academics

00:02:37.950 --> 00:02:40.610
and people at Berkeley, and myself.

00:02:40.610 --> 00:02:44.630
It's people who go around the globe

00:02:44.630 --> 00:02:48.690
and are not particularly
tied to the country

00:02:48.690 --> 00:02:51.327
in which they live,
academics are prone to this,

00:02:51.327 --> 00:02:54.180
and so are a lot of multi-national firms.

00:02:54.180 --> 00:02:57.530
And I know my university
does not consider itself

00:02:57.530 --> 00:03:02.530
an American university, we
are a global university,

00:03:02.620 --> 00:03:07.620
just the way IBM does not
consider itself an American firm.

00:03:07.770 --> 00:03:12.763
And the question is how this
can also weaken the things.

00:03:13.670 --> 00:03:16.487
So these are some things just to show you

00:03:16.487 --> 00:03:20.840
the historic and the Jefferson
and we have Hamilton,

00:03:20.840 --> 00:03:24.170
and the word here,
aristocracy is not a word

00:03:24.170 --> 00:03:27.100
we use particularly nowadays to refer

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:31.757
to things but Jefferson's concern,

00:03:31.757 --> 00:03:34.627
"The aristocracy of our
moneyed corporations."

00:03:37.050 --> 00:03:37.883
De Tocqueville was also worried

00:03:37.883 --> 00:03:39.190
that we would create this

00:03:40.340 --> 00:03:43.768
permanent inequality and aristocracy.

00:03:43.768 --> 00:03:48.120
Interestingly, Jefferson
was for free trade,

00:03:48.120 --> 00:03:49.900
so on the globalization debate,

00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:52.362
he would've been for globalization,

00:03:52.362 --> 00:03:55.010
but that was because the fear was

00:03:55.010 --> 00:03:59.700
that tariffs and other
protections from trade

00:03:59.700 --> 00:04:03.030
were gonna strengthen
the moneyed corporations.

00:04:03.030 --> 00:04:05.300
The farmers were not moneyed corporations,

00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:08.530
they were just the individuals working.

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:11.650
And Hamilton also, and that reflects

00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:14.130
the Hamilton Project that
the Brookings Institution,

00:04:14.130 --> 00:04:16.730
which I'll say more about,
'cause I really saw that

00:04:16.730 --> 00:04:18.861
as very interesting at
a Jefferson lecture.

00:04:18.861 --> 00:04:21.980
But it was not just more
aristocratic things,

00:04:21.980 --> 00:04:26.150
it was more expert decisions,
and we now have that,

00:04:26.150 --> 00:04:29.380
in large part, the Federal
Reserve will make some decisions

00:04:29.380 --> 00:04:32.677
today and tomorrow,
unelected set of people,

00:04:35.373 --> 00:04:37.120
experts, I personally have great faith

00:04:37.120 --> 00:04:39.960
in that Ben Bernanke will do good things

00:04:39.960 --> 00:04:41.740
and will try to make the best decisions,

00:04:41.740 --> 00:04:43.280
but nonetheless, it's very interesting

00:04:43.280 --> 00:04:46.640
that a lot of how the economy will operate

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:48.990
over the next, at least short term period,

00:04:48.990 --> 00:04:53.990
will depend upon experts, you
could call them aristocratic,

00:04:54.900 --> 00:04:56.780
but folks who were certainly not elected

00:04:56.780 --> 00:05:01.260
by anybody in our country,
and then John Jay,

00:05:01.260 --> 00:05:05.863
who was part of the
Hamilton gang, or group,

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:09.730
people who own the country
ought to govern it.

00:05:09.730 --> 00:05:12.410
That is not very helpful to democracy,

00:05:12.410 --> 00:05:15.343
so we'll now see the double specters.

00:05:16.560 --> 00:05:19.350
So this, I'll go very
quickly over the inequality,

00:05:19.350 --> 00:05:21.790
because I think there's
just widespread agreement

00:05:21.790 --> 00:05:26.040
and there can be no arguments about this.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:27.410
I started off with all the good things

00:05:27.410 --> 00:05:31.970
the US economy's done, and
we've been very successful

00:05:31.970 --> 00:05:36.240
in many ways, and we had excellent growth

00:05:36.240 --> 00:05:41.240
of GDP per capita over the
last, it's 16 years here.

00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:45.830
And then the skeleton is
our distribution of income.

00:05:45.830 --> 00:05:49.463
We have got an extraordinary
unequal distribution.

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:52.910
So let me give you some figures here,

00:05:52.910 --> 00:05:54.260
just so you see the nature of it.

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:59.260
The figure to the left
is, that's a 90/10 ratio,

00:06:00.151 --> 00:06:03.880
that's at the bottom, and at
the top is a GINI coefficient.

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:06.490
90/10 ratio takes the wages of the people

00:06:06.490 --> 00:06:08.960
in the 90th percentile and
divides it by the wages

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:10.710
of people in the 10th percentile.

00:06:10.710 --> 00:06:12.250
It's a measure of labor market.

00:06:12.250 --> 00:06:15.640
GINI coefficient is for the
overall income distribution.

00:06:15.640 --> 00:06:19.090
The dots are different
countries, advanced countries.

00:06:19.090 --> 00:06:22.970
So Japan, Canada, Britain, Germany,

00:06:22.970 --> 00:06:24.520
and we're out there, obviously,

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:27.210
number one in both of those metrics.

00:06:27.210 --> 00:06:31.620
The straight lines, the
bar graphs to the right,

00:06:31.620 --> 00:06:35.110
are to me the most remarkable indication

00:06:35.110 --> 00:06:39.050
of how unequal our country is.

00:06:39.050 --> 00:06:43.814
The first one is a standard
deviation of log earnings,

00:06:43.814 --> 00:06:46.490
which is an indicator, which
is a measure of earnings.

00:06:46.490 --> 00:06:49.790
Inequality, so higher
numbers are more unequal.

00:06:49.790 --> 00:06:54.790
So that's a 0.88, that's all Americans.

00:06:56.970 --> 00:06:58.980
Then you'd go and you'd take Americans

00:06:58.980 --> 00:07:03.980
who have the same score
on a global literacy test,

00:07:04.110 --> 00:07:07.710
which was done by the
OECD, was done in a lot

00:07:07.710 --> 00:07:10.623
of the, a number of advanced countries.

00:07:10.623 --> 00:07:14.320
And so those are people
with similar abilities,

00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:16.710
at least measured by a literacy score.

00:07:16.710 --> 00:07:19.180
And you can narrow that further,

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:21.710
you can do it by similar ability,

00:07:21.710 --> 00:07:26.238
exactly the same gender,
pretty much the same age,

00:07:26.238 --> 00:07:29.420
you could even look
within broad occupations,

00:07:29.420 --> 00:07:33.200
and you basically will get
similar results to this.

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:35.818
Anybody at Labor Conference who worked

00:07:35.818 --> 00:07:36.920
with earnings distributions, you know

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:39.670
that you put in all the controls you want

00:07:39.670 --> 00:07:42.850
and you're left with a lot of variability.

00:07:42.850 --> 00:07:45.240
And I like thinking about that as,

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:48.690
you have students in
exactly the same class,

00:07:48.690 --> 00:07:51.840
all scoring reasonably well on an exam,

00:07:51.840 --> 00:07:53.720
and look at them 10 years later.

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:56.167
You will see, again, the same degree

00:07:56.167 --> 00:07:58.757
and the same university, I'm
thinking of my own students

00:07:58.757 --> 00:08:01.490
in the 10 year class of
economics at Harvard.

00:08:01.490 --> 00:08:03.970
And when they graduate
and go 10 years later,

00:08:03.970 --> 00:08:07.340
you'll have the investment
banker making huge sums,

00:08:07.340 --> 00:08:10.140
you'll have the graduate student

00:08:13.024 --> 00:08:16.060
not making huge sums, as we know,

00:08:16.060 --> 00:08:19.090
and you'll have a just
incredible dispersion.

00:08:19.090 --> 00:08:21.410
Then, because of this dataset,

00:08:21.410 --> 00:08:24.640
we were able to get figures
for Germany, all workers,

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:27.500
Netherlands and Sweden,
and the stunning thing

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:30.530
is the inequality in the US of people

00:08:30.530 --> 00:08:32.540
with the same scores, and I say,

00:08:32.540 --> 00:08:33.810
you could break that down more,

00:08:33.810 --> 00:08:36.820
exceeds the inequality in earnings

00:08:36.820 --> 00:08:39.860
in those three European
countries of everybody.

00:08:39.860 --> 00:08:42.730
That's people who can't read
and people who can read.

00:08:42.730 --> 00:08:45.367
People in good jobs
and people in bad jobs.

00:08:45.367 --> 00:08:47.420
That's just indication, yeah,

00:08:47.420 --> 00:08:50.360
we're really far out in this inequality.

00:08:50.360 --> 00:08:54.633
Then I have some figures
from the CIA World Factbook.

00:08:55.570 --> 00:08:57.090
There are other figures I could've chosen,

00:08:57.090 --> 00:08:59.128
but I chose that one because I thought

00:08:59.128 --> 00:09:01.380
some of my conservative
friends might be very critical,

00:09:01.380 --> 00:09:05.400
and I would say, well,
it's from the CIA, guys,

00:09:05.400 --> 00:09:06.500
so what do you expect?

00:09:07.556 --> 00:09:10.140
So there is the GINI coefficients,

00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:13.360
and you know, higher GINI
coefficient is more inequality,

00:09:13.360 --> 00:09:16.380
so India was lower than
I would've expected,

00:09:16.380 --> 00:09:20.640
and maybe the figures are
not so accurate, 0.33,

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:24.330
China is 0.44, the US is 0.45.

00:09:24.330 --> 00:09:28.243
US and China have basically
the same inequality of income.

00:09:31.230 --> 00:09:34.460
In the 118 countries for
which the World Factbook

00:09:34.460 --> 00:09:36.160
gave data, the US was 84th.

00:09:38.995 --> 00:09:43.995
So that's not, that's 84th, is
meaning very low in equality.

00:09:44.567 --> 00:09:47.023
We're very unequal, yeah.

00:09:47.952 --> 00:09:50.440
And the bottom half of
developing countries.

00:09:50.440 --> 00:09:53.470
I was stunned at that as
well, but this is all just,

00:09:53.470 --> 00:09:58.310
this is that we have a
serious inequality problem

00:09:58.310 --> 00:10:01.750
or issue or facts, at least.

00:10:01.750 --> 00:10:05.343
We've also seen, over the last 30 years,

00:10:06.626 --> 00:10:07.750
and 30 years, meaning it's been

00:10:07.750 --> 00:10:10.120
through Republican administrations,

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:12.020
it's been through
Democratic administrations,

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:14.390
it's not a partisan kind of fact.

00:10:14.390 --> 00:10:16.640
The facts aren't partisan, in any case.

00:10:16.640 --> 00:10:19.350
And the blue line with the dots

00:10:19.350 --> 00:10:23.670
is the growth of, is the
level of real hourly earnings

00:10:25.256 --> 00:10:28.290
from the series that's the longest

00:10:28.290 --> 00:10:30.180
and the most extensive that we had.

00:10:30.180 --> 00:10:33.410
The top line with the little triangles,

00:10:33.410 --> 00:10:34.960
that's productivity growth.

00:10:34.960 --> 00:10:38.245
Productivity growth, and
it's all centered around,

00:10:38.245 --> 00:10:41.280
19, I think, 70 was the year I picked,

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:46.280
for just locking it as 100,
and then it just grows.

00:10:47.090 --> 00:10:48.960
You see it just spanning out,

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:53.880
and you see the productivity
growth has been very good,

00:10:53.880 --> 00:10:55.910
and real wage growth is not.

00:10:55.910 --> 00:10:58.230
The intermediate lines
are different measures

00:10:58.230 --> 00:11:00.650
of different real wage serieses.

00:11:00.650 --> 00:11:02.540
So there's a number of different series

00:11:02.540 --> 00:11:04.739
that one can look at, some include

00:11:04.739 --> 00:11:09.739
non-wage compensation such
as pensions and healthcare,

00:11:10.290 --> 00:11:13.280
et cetera, but whichever one you pick,

00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:16.810
it's clearly that productivity growth

00:11:16.810 --> 00:11:19.460
has been very good and
none of the real wages

00:11:19.460 --> 00:11:22.440
of American workers
have gone up that much.

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:24.442
So we've had a rising,

00:11:24.442 --> 00:11:28.630
this obviously produces rising inequality.

00:11:28.630 --> 00:11:32.410
Well, productivity growth
has helped some people,

00:11:32.410 --> 00:11:34.260
and hopefully these gentlemen

00:11:34.260 --> 00:11:39.260
will contribute money to our
university, our universities,

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:42.750
and we'll have a naming
ceremony for this room

00:11:42.750 --> 00:11:45.800
or something, and I don't know how much

00:11:45.800 --> 00:11:48.137
they would change this
from the Jefferson Lecture

00:11:48.137 --> 00:11:51.569
to the Big Bucks Lecture if Mr. Big Bucks

00:11:51.569 --> 00:11:53.430
would give the money, but it's clear

00:11:53.430 --> 00:11:55.800
these people have done extremely well,

00:11:55.800 --> 00:11:57.450
these very wealthy people.

00:11:57.450 --> 00:12:00.160
So I wanna give you some extreme views

00:12:00.160 --> 00:12:01.960
of the American income distribution.

00:12:02.900 --> 00:12:07.170
And the perfect payday, CIOs reap millions

00:12:07.170 --> 00:12:10.060
by landing stock options
when they are most valuable.

00:12:10.060 --> 00:12:12.063
Luck, or something else?

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.470
Great CEO Pay Heist, you can read them.

00:12:17.470 --> 00:12:19.400
And then the one that I was stunned at

00:12:19.400 --> 00:12:22.143
when I saw, in late September 2001,

00:12:22.143 --> 00:12:26.720
right after the World Trade
Center and Pentagon attacks,

00:12:26.720 --> 00:12:29.540
I didn't realize scores
of companies ladled out

00:12:29.540 --> 00:12:33.330
options to executives worth millions.

00:12:33.330 --> 00:12:36.210
So they immediately said,
the stock market falls,

00:12:36.210 --> 00:12:37.930
we know it's gonna bounce back

00:12:39.700 --> 00:12:41.850
because right now people are in a panic,

00:12:41.850 --> 00:12:43.460
so what do we do, the first thing we do

00:12:43.460 --> 00:12:45.160
is we give options to ourselves

00:12:45.160 --> 00:12:48.300
dated now that the stock
market is way down.

00:12:48.300 --> 00:12:49.950
So this particular gentleman calls it

00:12:49.950 --> 00:12:52.850
sleazeballs and profiteering ghouls,

00:12:52.850 --> 00:12:54.520
is that what business is about?

00:12:54.520 --> 00:12:56.060
And then the last one is another,

00:12:56.060 --> 00:12:57.350
these are very radical statements.

00:12:57.350 --> 00:13:01.143
I would regard these as
incredibly extreme statements.

00:13:02.400 --> 00:13:03.944
Where are they from?

00:13:03.944 --> 00:13:07.410
You might've been guessing, Jones?

00:13:07.410 --> 00:13:11.090
It's the Wall Street
Journal, Fortune magazine,

00:13:11.090 --> 00:13:14.870
the story that had not really,

00:13:14.870 --> 00:13:16.480
far as I know, gotten very much attention

00:13:16.480 --> 00:13:18.230
was these executives writing these options

00:13:18.230 --> 00:13:21.070
for themselves right after the attack,

00:13:21.070 --> 00:13:23.650
that was the editor of the
Harvard Business Review,

00:13:23.650 --> 00:13:26.913
and this was on a PBS broadcast.

00:13:28.230 --> 00:13:30.080
And then Forbes magazine.

00:13:30.080 --> 00:13:33.430
So this is reading of,
prior to what's happened

00:13:33.430 --> 00:13:35.980
in the inequality in the country,

00:13:35.980 --> 00:13:39.320
from, you can't get more conservative

00:13:39.320 --> 00:13:41.580
than these four organizations,

00:13:41.580 --> 00:13:43.990
you know, and conservative
and honest and reputable

00:13:43.990 --> 00:13:47.110
and so on, you know, Forbes,
Fortune, Wall Street Journal,

00:13:47.110 --> 00:13:48.820
exclusive of the editorial page

00:13:48.820 --> 00:13:51.520
is a pretty accurate place,

00:13:51.520 --> 00:13:54.450
and the Harvard Business
Review, that's pretty accurate.

00:13:54.450 --> 00:13:58.730
So that's some striking, if I say,

00:13:58.730 --> 00:14:00.280
I don't think there can be any argument

00:14:00.280 --> 00:14:02.902
about what's happened to
the income distribution

00:14:02.902 --> 00:14:07.902
in the country and that
something is awry with this.

00:14:08.090 --> 00:14:11.850
And then there's another
radical commentary,

00:14:11.850 --> 00:14:13.530
and this is from Warren Buffett.

00:14:13.530 --> 00:14:14.800
You may have noticed that he's been making

00:14:14.800 --> 00:14:17.960
a number of comments since he's given away

00:14:17.960 --> 00:14:21.810
his 40 billion dollars or so
to the Bill Gates Foundation,

00:14:21.810 --> 00:14:24.870
or 30 billion, and this
was a statement though,

00:14:24.870 --> 00:14:26.785
he made to his shareholders,

00:14:26.785 --> 00:14:29.570
in which, the best line in this

00:14:29.570 --> 00:14:31.527
is the one right towards the end,

00:14:31.527 --> 00:14:34.477
"If class warfare is
being waged in America,

00:14:34.477 --> 00:14:37.430
"my class is clearly winning."

00:14:37.430 --> 00:14:40.410
And then he goes on and points out

00:14:40.410 --> 00:14:45.410
that he paid a lower tax
than his receptionist,

00:14:46.980 --> 00:14:48.310
and of course, what's going on there

00:14:48.310 --> 00:14:52.160
is it's Social Security,
which is top coded,

00:14:52.160 --> 00:14:56.355
so you stopped at the
top, and she's paying that

00:14:56.355 --> 00:14:59.240
and he's not, on the margin,
so his marginal tax rate

00:14:59.240 --> 00:15:02.400
is actually lower than
hers, and he's quite upset

00:15:02.400 --> 00:15:05.130
about this, so I think
if we got all these,

00:15:05.130 --> 00:15:09.786
the Wall Street Journal, and the Forbes,

00:15:09.786 --> 00:15:11.090
and the Harvard Business Review,

00:15:11.090 --> 00:15:13.189
and we have one of the country's second,

00:15:13.189 --> 00:15:15.150
he was till he gave away all his money,

