00:30:22.560 --> 00:30:25.120
and some more radicalish person than I,

00:30:25.120 --> 00:30:27.970
jumped on me for having
said that US GDP growth

00:30:27.970 --> 00:30:29.820
was very good, which it has been.

00:30:29.820 --> 00:30:32.717
And then he said, "Well, what
difference does that make?

00:30:32.717 --> 00:30:34.887
"Most people haven't had
real income increases,

00:30:34.887 --> 00:30:37.100
"or had very small real income increases."

00:30:37.100 --> 00:30:39.220
And then, that is the point here.

00:30:39.220 --> 00:30:41.913
You got growth of GDP,
which economists like,

00:30:43.201 --> 00:30:44.473
the privileges that we should see,

00:30:44.473 --> 00:30:46.020
good growth of GDP, that's
what we always look for,

00:30:46.020 --> 00:30:48.725
for the papers, and it
can be very different

00:30:48.725 --> 00:30:50.220
than growth of citizen wellbeing.

00:30:50.220 --> 00:30:51.860
And that's partly the story of the US

00:30:51.860 --> 00:30:53.770
over the last, I think, 30 years.

00:30:53.770 --> 00:30:57.550
And, I said, in reducing
the scope for government

00:30:57.550 --> 00:31:02.550
to operate, and if we go
through this transition period

00:31:03.040 --> 00:31:06.060
of adjusting to China and
India catching up with us

00:31:06.060 --> 00:31:09.780
in education, catching
up with us in technology,

00:31:09.780 --> 00:31:11.610
catching up with us in lots of stuff,

00:31:11.610 --> 00:31:14.900
can be a very difficult transition

00:31:14.900 --> 00:31:16.940
without, I think, democratic oversight

00:31:16.940 --> 00:31:20.482
and I call it the fair
distribution of benefits and costs,

00:31:20.482 --> 00:31:22.360
which is important.

00:31:22.360 --> 00:31:25.231
I'll talk about the
inequality in politics.

